1. What is a Loop?

A loop lets you repeat code multiple times until a condition is met or until you run out of items to process.
ðŸ‘‰ Without loops â†’ you repeat code manually.
ðŸ‘‰ With loops â†’ Python does repetition for you.

2. Types of Loops
ðŸ”¹ for loop â€“ iterate over a sequence (list, string, range, etc.)
for i in range(5):
    print(i)   # 0,1,2,3,4


range(n) â†’ generates numbers from 0 to n-1.

Commonly used when you know how many times you need to loop.

ðŸ”¹ while loop â€“ repeat while condition is True
x = 0
while x < 5:
    print(x)
    x += 1


Used when you donâ€™t know how many times in advance.

3. Loop Control Keywords

break â†’ stop loop immediately.

for i in range(10):
    if i == 5:
        break
    print(i)


continue â†’ skip current iteration.

for i in range(5):
    if i == 2:
        continue
    print(i)


pass â†’ do nothing (placeholder).

for i in range(3):
    pass


else with loops â†’ runs if loop ends naturally (not via break).

for i in range(3):
    print(i)
else:
    print("Loop finished!")

4. Iteration Over Different Objects

List:

for fruit in ["apple", "banana", "mango"]:
    print(fruit)


String:

for ch in "Python":
    print(ch)


Dictionary:

student = {"name": "Swathy", "age": 30}
for key, value in student.items():
    print(key, ":", value)

5. Smart Things to Know

âœ… Use range(start, stop, step) for numbers.

for i in range(2, 10, 2):  # even numbers
    print(i)


âœ… Use enumerate() for index + value.

names = ["A", "B", "C"]
for index, value in enumerate(names):
    print(index, value)


âœ… Use zip() to loop over two lists together.

names = ["A", "B", "C"]
scores = [85, 90, 95]
for n, s in zip(names, scores):
    print(n, s)


âœ… Use list comprehension â†’ shorter + cleaner loop.

squares = [x*x for x in range(5)]
print(squares)  # [0,1,4,9,16]

6. Doâ€™s & Donâ€™ts

âœ… Doâ€™s:

Keep loops short and readable.

Use break to prevent infinite loops.

Use enumerate() & zip() instead of manual index tracking.

Use list comprehensions for creating lists efficiently.

âŒ Donâ€™ts:

Donâ€™t forget to update variables in while loops â†’ infinite loop risk.

Donâ€™t use loops when Python already has built-ins (sum(), max(), etc.).

Donâ€™t put heavy tasks inside nested loops unless necessary.

7. Pitfalls to Watch

Infinite loop example:

x = 0
while x < 5:
    print(x)   # forgot x += 1 â†’ runs forever


Modifying list while iterating â†’ unexpected results.

nums = [1,2,3]
for n in nums:
    nums.remove(n)  # BAD

8. Pro Smart Tips

Use any() and all() for conditions instead of manual loops.

nums = [1,2,3,4]
print(all(n > 0 for n in nums))  # True
print(any(n > 3 for n in nums))  # True


Use generator expressions for memory efficiency:

gen = (x*x for x in range(1000000))
print(next(gen))  # 0
print(next(gen))  # 1


ðŸ’¡ Golden Rule:
ðŸ‘‰ Use for when looping over known sequences.
ðŸ‘‰ Use while when looping until a condition changes.